## Suggested quick workaround: fallback to `issues.jsonl`

When `bd list --json` returns non-JSON output (detected by checking if the response starts with `[` or `{`), the viewer could fall back to reading `.beads/issues.jsonl` directly.

This file is already maintained by `bd export` (auto-sync hook writes it after every bd write operation). In our case it has 544 lines of valid JSONL with the same schema the viewer already parses in `parse_issues_tolerant()`.

**Why this is better than direct Dolt access:**
- Zero new dependencies (no MySQL client needed)
- The file already exists and is kept up-to-date
- Same JSON format the viewer already understands
- Works as a read-only fallback — write operations (create/update/delete) can still go through `bd` CLI (those commands work fine, only `bd list --json` is broken)

**Pseudocode:**
```rust
fn bd_list(...) -> Result<Vec<Issue>, String> {
    let output = execute_bd("list", &args, cwd)?;

    // Try JSON parse
    match parse_issues_tolerant(&output, "bd_list") {
        Ok(issues) => Ok(issues),
        Err(_) if project_uses_dolt(&beads_dir) => {
            // Fallback: read issues.jsonl directly
            let jsonl = std::fs::read_to_string(beads_dir.join("issues.jsonl"))?;
            parse_jsonl_issues(&jsonl)  // line-by-line JSON parse
        }
        Err(e) => Err(e),
    }
}
```

This would immediately restore read functionality for all users affected by the `bd 0.59.0` regression (steveyegge/beads#2395), without waiting for an upstream fix.
